Note: ============================================================================
Note: POWERSHELL SEMANTIC ANALYZER
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Semantic analysis for PowerShell automation framework
Note: Handles PowerShell-specific features:
Note: - Object-oriented pipeline and cmdlets
Note: - .NET type system integration
Note: - PowerShell modules and snap-ins
Note: - Variable scoping and automatic variables
Note: - PowerShell drives and providers
Note: - Advanced functions and parameters
Note: - Error handling and try-catch-finally
Note: - PowerShell classes and enums
Note: - Workflow and DSC (Desired State Configuration)
Note: - Remote execution and sessions

Import from "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_nodes.runa" use HIRNode, HIRStatement, HIRExpression, HIRType
Import from "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir_builder.runa" use HIRBuilder

@Reasoning:
Top-level analyzer state. Mirrors PowerShell's runtime environment:
current_scope chains back to parent through PowerShellScope.parent_scope;
loaded_modules tracks Import-Module imports; cmdlet_registry, type_
accelerators (the [int]/[string] aliases), automatic_variables, and
psdrive_providers (FileSystem:, Registry:, etc.) provide name resolution.
execution_policy/powershell_version/is_ise_environment/is_core_edition
capture environment-specific knobs that affect what cmdlets are
available and which APIs validate.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellSemanticContext":
    current_scope as PowerShellScope
    parent_context as PowerShellSemanticContext
    loaded_modules as List[String]
    current_function as String
    error_list as List[String]
    warning_list as List[String]
    cmdlet_registry as Dictionary[String, PowerShellCmdlet]
    type_accelerators as Dictionary[String, String]
    automatic_variables as Dictionary[String, PowerShellVariable]
    psdrive_providers as Dictionary[String, PowerShellProvider]
    execution_policy as String
    powershell_version as String
    is_ise_environment as Boolean
    is_core_edition as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
A PowerShell lexical scope. PowerShell scopes are richer than most
languages: a scope can be global, script, function, or local; PS also
supports explicit "$private:" modifiers that prevent inheritance. The
boolean flags (is_global/is_script/is_function/is_private) encode that
classification so name-lookup can apply the right inheritance rules.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellScope":
    variables as Dictionary[String, PowerShellVariable]
    functions as Dictionary[String, PowerShellFunction]
    aliases as Dictionary[String, String]
    parent_scope as PowerShellScope
    scope_type as String
    scope_id as Integer
    is_global as Boolean
    is_script as Boolean
    is_function as Boolean
    is_private as Boolean
End Type

Note: Local PowerShell AST schema used by this semantic analyzer until
Note: v0.0.9.x replaces it with generic HIRNode traversal.
@Reasoning:
Wide-field AST view exposing named slots per PowerShell node kind
(pipeline_elements for command chains, function_name vs command_name to
distinguish function invocations from cmdlet calls, scope_modifier for
"$global:" / "$script:" / "$private:" prefixes, is_splatting for "@var"
argument expansion, param_block for the param() declaration block).
Unused fields for a given node-kind remain 0; type is the textual type
constraint when one is declared.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellSemNode":
    node_type as String
    name as Integer
    line as Integer
    body as Integer
    arguments as Integer
    parameters as Integer
    attributes as Integer
    pipeline_elements as Integer
    function_name as Integer
    command_name as Integer
    variable_name as Integer
    scope_modifier as Integer
    param_block as Integer
    is_splatting as Integer
    type as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
PowerShell variable record. Tracks PowerShell-specific traits: is_constant
(Set-Variable -Option Constant); is_readonly (-Option ReadOnly), one-time
assignment); is_automatic (built-in like $_, $?, $args); is_preference
(built-in preference variable like $ErrorActionPreference). The
attributes list holds parameter validation attributes
([ValidateRange(...)], [ValidateNotNull()], etc.) when the variable
declares them.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellVariable":
    name as String
    value as String
    type as PowerShellType
    scope as String
    is_constant as Boolean
    is_readonly as Boolean
    is_private as Boolean
    is_automatic as Boolean
    is_preference as Boolean
    description as String
    first_assignment_line as Integer
    last_access_line as Integer
    attributes as List[String]
End Type

@Reasoning:
PowerShell function metadata. is_advanced functions use [CmdletBinding()]
to gain cmdlet-like features (common parameters, parameter sets); is_filter
runs once per pipeline element; is_workflow tags a PowerShell Workflow
(parallel execution semantics). help_info carries the comment-based help
parsed from "<#...#>" blocks at the top of the function body.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellFunction":
    name as String
    parameters as List[PowerShellParameter]
    body as PowerShellSemNode
    return_type as PowerShellType
    is_advanced as Boolean
    is_filter as Boolean
    is_workflow as Boolean
    cmdlet_binding as Boolean
    help_info as PowerShellHelpInfo
    attributes as List[String]
    output_type as List[String]
End Type

@Reasoning:
PowerShell parameter record exposing the full [Parameter()] attribute
surface: mandatory/positional/ValueFromPipeline/ValueFromPipelineByPropertyName
flags, parameter-set membership for multi-set cmdlets, help message,
default value, and validation attributes ([ValidateRange], [ValidatePattern],
[ValidateSet], etc.). The alias_names list captures any [Alias(...)]
attribute aliases that resolve to this parameter.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellParameter":
    name as String
    type as PowerShellType
    is_mandatory as Boolean
    is_pipeline_input as Boolean
    pipeline_property_name as String
    position as Integer
    parameter_set as String
    help_message as String
    default_value as String
    validation_attributes as List[String]
    alias_names as List[String]
End Type

@Reasoning:
A PowerShell cmdlet (binary cmdlet, advanced function, or proxy command).
verb/noun separation is mandatory (Get-Process, Set-Location, etc.). The
multi-parameter_sets list models cmdlets that accept different combinations
of parameters (e.g. Get-ChildItem -Path vs -LiteralPath); the parameter
list union is precomputed for fast lookup. requires_elevation flags
cmdlets that need administrator privileges (Stop-Service in some
contexts, Set-ExecutionPolicy with MachinePolicy scope, etc.).
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellCmdlet":
    name as String
    verb as String
    noun as String
    parameters as List[PowerShellParameter]
    parameter_sets as List[PowerShellParameterSet]
    input_types as List[String]
    output_types as List[String]
    module_name as String
    command_type as String
    help_info as PowerShellHelpInfo
    is_core_cmdlet as Boolean
    requires_elevation as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
A named parameter set as declared via [Parameter(ParameterSetName=...)].
Only one parameter set is active per invocation; PS uses the bound
parameter combination to choose which set applies. The is_default flag
marks the set that is used when no parameter combination uniquely
selects a set.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellParameterSet":
    name as String
    parameters as List[String]
    is_default as Boolean
End Type

@Reasoning:
PowerShell type record bridging the .NET type system. Tracks the
type's CLR namespace and containing assembly so [System.IO.FileInfo]
can be resolved to System.IO from mscorlib. Distinguishes value vs
reference types for correct copy semantics, arrays from collections
(both index but only arrays have a fixed-length contiguous layout),
and exposes element_type and generic_arguments for parameterized
types like List[string].
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellType":
    name as String
    namespace as String
    assembly as String
    is_value_type as Boolean
    is_reference_type as Boolean
    is_array as Boolean
    is_collection as Boolean
    element_type as PowerShellType
    generic_arguments as List[PowerShellType]
End Type

@Reasoning:
A PowerShell provider (FileSystem, Registry, Variable, Function, etc.)
that exposes a hierarchical namespace through PSDrives. The drives list
records which named PSDrives this provider has registered ("C:" / "HKLM:"
/ "Variable:" etc.) and capabilities reports which provider operations
(Item, Container, Drive, ShouldProcess) are supported.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellProvider":
    name as String
    drives as List[String]
    capabilities as List[String]
    description as String
    module_name as String
End Type

@Reasoning:
Comment-based help record parsed from PowerShell function/cmdlet help
blocks. Mirrors the .SYNOPSIS, .DESCRIPTION, .PARAMETER, .EXAMPLE,
.NOTES, .LINK comment directives. The parameters dict maps each
parameter name to its help-comment description so Get-Help can render
per-parameter documentation.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellHelpInfo":
    synopsis as String
    description as String
    parameters as Dictionary[String, String]
    examples as List[String]
    notes as String
    links as List[String]
End Type

@Reasoning:
A semantic diagnostic record. severity is "error"/"warning"/"info" and
error_code is a stable identifier (e.g. "PS:undefined") that downstream
tooling can pattern-match on without parsing the human-readable
message.
@End Reasoning
Type called "PowerShellSemanticError":
    message as String
    line as Integer
    column as Integer
    severity as String
    error_code as String
End Type

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MAIN SEMANTIC ANALYSIS ENTRY POINT
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "analyze_powershell_semantics" that takes ast as PowerShellSemNode returns PowerShellSemanticContext:
    Note: Main entry point for PowerShell semantic analysis

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell has sophisticated semantic requirements including object
    pipeline semantics, .NET type integration, cmdlet parameter binding,
    and complex scoping rules with automatic variables.
    @End Reasoning

    Let context be create_global_powershell_context

    Note: Load PowerShell core modules and cmdlets
    Call load_powershell_core with context

    Note: Analyze the AST
    Call analyze_powershell_node with ast and context

    Note: Perform final validation
    Call validate_powershell_semantics with context

    Return context
End Process

@Reasoning:
Constructs the top-level analyzer context with empty registries and a
fresh global scope. The global scope is_global=true so subsequent
scope-walks know when they have reached the top of the chain. The
returned context still needs load_powershell_core called to populate
the built-in cmdlets/variables/aliases.
@End Reasoning
Process called "create_global_powershell_context" that takes nothing returns PowerShellSemanticContext:
    Note: Create the global semantic context with PowerShell environment

    Let global_scope be a value of type PowerShellScope with
        variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        functions as a dictionary containing nothing,
        aliases as a dictionary containing nothing,
        parent_scope as null,
        scope_type as "Global",
        scope_id as 0,
        is_global as true,
        is_script as false,
        is_function as false,
        is_private as false

    Let context be a value of type PowerShellSemanticContext with
        current_scope as global_scope,
        parent_context as null,
        loaded_modules as a list containing "Microsoft.PowerShell.Core", "Microsoft.PowerShell.Management", "Microsoft.PowerShell.Security", "Microsoft.PowerShell.Utility",
        current_function as null,
        error_list as a list containing nothing,
        warning_list as a list containing nothing,
        cmdlet_registry as a dictionary containing nothing,
        type_accelerators as a dictionary containing nothing,
        automatic_variables as a dictionary containing nothing,
        psdrive_providers as a dictionary containing nothing,
        execution_policy as "Restricted",
        powershell_version as "5.1",
        is_ise_environment as false,
        is_core_edition as false

    Return context
End Process

Process called "load_powershell_core" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load PowerShell core modules and built-in functionality

    @Reasoning:
    PowerShell comes with extensive built-in cmdlets, automatic variables,
    type accelerators, and providers that form the foundation of the
    PowerShell execution environment.
    @End Reasoning

    Note: Load automatic variables
    Call load_automatic_variables with ctx

    Note: Load type accelerators
    Call load_type_accelerators with ctx

    Note: Load core cmdlets
    Call load_core_cmdlets with ctx

    Note: Load management cmdlets
    Call load_management_cmdlets with ctx

    Note: Load utility cmdlets
    Call load_utility_cmdlets with ctx

    Note: Load security cmdlets
    Call load_security_cmdlets with ctx

    Note: Load providers
    Call load_powershell_providers with ctx

    Note: Load common aliases
    Call load_common_aliases with ctx
End Process

@Reasoning:
Pre-populates the automatic_variables dictionary with PowerShell's
built-in implicit variables: $_, $args, $error, $true/$false/$null,
$HOME, $PSScriptRoot, $MyInvocation, $PSCommandPath, etc. Each entry
has is_automatic=true so the validator does not flag undefined-name
errors for references to them.
@End Reasoning
Process called "load_automatic_variables" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load PowerShell automatic variables

    Let auto_vars be a list containing:
        create_automatic_variable with "$_" and "current pipeline object",
        create_automatic_variable with "$?" and "execution status of last command",
        create_automatic_variable with "$^" and "first token of last line",
        create_automatic_variable with "$$" and "last token of last line",
        create_automatic_variable with "$Args" and "array of undeclared parameters",
        create_automatic_variable with "$Error" and "array of error objects",
        create_automatic_variable with "$ExecutionContext" and "execution context",
        create_automatic_variable with "$false" and "boolean false value",
        create_automatic_variable with "$true" and "boolean true value",
        create_automatic_variable with "$Host" and "current host program",
        create_automatic_variable with "$HOME" and "user's home directory",
        create_automatic_variable with "$LastExitCode" and "exit code of last program",
        create_automatic_variable with "$Matches" and "regex match results",
        create_automatic_variable with "$MyInvocation" and "invocation information",
        create_automatic_variable with "$null" and "null/empty value",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PID" and "process identifier",
        create_automatic_variable with "$Profile" and "PowerShell profile paths",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PSBoundParameters" and "bound parameters",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PSCmdlet" and "current cmdlet",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PSCommandPath" and "script path",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PSHome" and "PowerShell installation directory",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PSScriptRoot" and "script directory",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PSVersionTable" and "PowerShell version information",
        create_automatic_variable with "$PWD" and "current working directory",
        create_automatic_variable with "$ShellId" and "current shell identifier"

    For Each var as PowerShellVariable in auto_vars:
        Set ctx.automatic_variables at key var.name to var
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Loads PowerShell's type-accelerator dictionary mapping short names to
fully-qualified .NET type names ([int] -> System.Int32, [string] ->
System.String, [hashtable] -> System.Collections.Hashtable, etc.). Lets
parser-level [shortname] type constraints resolve to full CLR types
during semantic checking.
@End Reasoning
Process called "load_type_accelerators" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load PowerShell type accelerators

    Let accelerators be a dictionary containing:
        "int" as "System.Int32",
        "long" as "System.Int64",
        "string" as "System.String",
        "char" as "System.Char",
        "bool" as "System.Boolean",
        "byte" as "System.Byte",
        "double" as "System.Double",
        "decimal" as "System.Decimal",
        "float" as "System.Single",
        "single" as "System.Single",
        "array" as "System.Array",
        "xml" as "System.Xml.XmlDocument",
        "xmldoc" as "System.Xml.XmlDocument",
        "hashtable" as "System.Collections.Hashtable",
        "datetime" as "System.DateTime",
        "timespan" as "System.TimeSpan",
        "regex" as "System.Text.RegularExpressions.Regex",
        "guid" as "System.Guid",
        "uri" as "System.Uri",
        "version" as "System.Version",
        "mailaddress" as "System.Net.Mail.MailAddress",
        "ipaddress" as "System.Net.IPAddress",
        "wmi" as "System.Management.ManagementObject",
        "wmisearcher" as "System.Management.ManagementObjectSearcher",
        "wmiclass" as "System.Management.ManagementClass",
        "adsi" as "System.DirectoryServices.DirectoryEntry",
        "adsisearcher" as "System.DirectoryServices.DirectorySearcher",
        "psobject" as "System.Management.Automation.PSObject",
        "pscustomobject" as "System.Management.Automation.PSObject",
        "powershell" as "System.Management.Automation.PowerShell",
        "runspace" as "System.Management.Automation.Runspaces.Runspace",
        "runspacefactory" as "System.Management.Automation.Runspaces.RunspaceFactory"

    Set ctx.type_accelerators to accelerators
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers PowerShell's Microsoft.PowerShell.Core cmdlets (Get-Command,
Get-Help, Get-Module, Import-Module, Where-Object, ForEach-Object,
New-Object, etc.). These are the always-available core cmdlets that do
not require any external module import.
@End Reasoning
Process called "load_core_cmdlets" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load PowerShell Core module cmdlets

    Let core_cmdlets be a list containing:
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Command" and "Get" and "Command",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Help" and "Get" and "Help",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-History" and "Get" and "History",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Add-History" and "Add" and "History",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Clear-History" and "Clear" and "History",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Invoke-History" and "Invoke" and "History",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Job" and "Get" and "Job",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Start-Job" and "Start" and "Job",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Stop-Job" and "Stop" and "Job",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Wait-Job" and "Wait" and "Job",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Remove-Job" and "Remove" and "Job",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Receive-Job" and "Receive" and "Job",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Module" and "Get" and "Module",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Import-Module" and "Import" and "Module",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Remove-Module" and "Remove" and "Module",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "New-Module" and "New" and "Module",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Test-ModuleManifest" and "Test" and "ModuleManifest",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-PSSession" and "Get" and "PSSession",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "New-PSSession" and "New" and "PSSession",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Enter-PSSession" and "Enter" and "PSSession",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Exit-PSSession" and "Exit" and "PSSession",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Remove-PSSession" and "Remove" and "PSSession",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Invoke-Command" and "Invoke" and "Command",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Enable-PSRemoting" and "Enable" and "PSRemoting",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Disable-PSRemoting" and "Disable" and "PSRemoting"

    For Each cmdlet in core_cmdlets:
        Set ctx.cmdlet_registry at key cmdlet.name to cmdlet
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the Microsoft.PowerShell.Management cmdlets (Get-ChildItem,
Set-Location, Get-Process, Stop-Service, Get-Content, Copy-Item, etc.).
These are filesystem, process, and service management primitives bundled
with PowerShell by default.
@End Reasoning
Process called "load_management_cmdlets" that takes ctx as PowerShellSemanticContext returns Nothing:
    Note: Load PowerShell Management module cmdlets

    Let mgmt_cmdlets be a list containing:
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Location" and "Get" and "Location",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Set-Location" and "Set" and "Location",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Push-Location" and "Push" and "Location",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Pop-Location" and "Pop" and "Location",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-ChildItem" and "Get" and "ChildItem",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "New-Item" and "New" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Set-Item" and "Set" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Remove-Item" and "Remove" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Copy-Item" and "Copy" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Move-Item" and "Move" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Rename-Item" and "Rename" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Clear-Item" and "Clear" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Invoke-Item" and "Invoke" and "Item",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-ItemProperty" and "Get" and "ItemProperty",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Set-ItemProperty" and "Set" and "ItemProperty",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "New-ItemProperty" and "New" and "ItemProperty",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Remove-ItemProperty" and "Remove" and "ItemProperty",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Clear-ItemProperty" and "Clear" and "ItemProperty",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Content" and "Get" and "Content",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Set-Content" and "Set" and "Content",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Add-Content" and "Add" and "Content",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Clear-Content" and "Clear" and "Content",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Process" and "Get" and "Process",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Start-Process" and "Start" and "Process",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Stop-Process" and "Stop" and "Process",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Wait-Process" and "Wait" and "Process",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Debug-Process" and "Debug" and "Process",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Get-Service" and "Get" and "Service",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Start-Service" and "Start" and "Service",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Stop-Service" and "Stop" and "Service",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Restart-Service" and "Restart" and "Service",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Suspend-Service" and "Suspend" and "Service",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Resume-Service" and "Resume" and "Service",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "New-Service" and "New" and "Service",
        create_powershell_cmdlet with "Set-Service" and "Set" and "Service"

    For Each cmdlet in mgmt_cmdlets:
        Set ctx.cmdlet_registry at key cmdlet.name to cmdlet
    End For
End Process

@Reasoning:
Registers the Microsoft.PowerShell.Utility cmdlets (Write-Host,
Write-Output, ConvertTo-Json, ConvertFrom-Json, Measure-Object,
Select-Object, Sort-Object, Group-Object, etc.). These are the
general-purpose data-shape and output cmdlets.
@End Reasoning
